			<h3 class="first"><a href="#p164186">わりに／くせに／ても／のに</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/viewtopic.php?p=164186&amp;sid=afdf1483b436d49534d9f60bd1de6d37#p164186"><img src="http://thejapanesepage.com/phpbb/styles/tjp-embed/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=94193&amp;sid=afdf1483b436d49534d9f60bd1de6d37">DarumaBlue</a></strong> &raquo; Fri 04.09.2010 2:30 am </p>

			

			<div class="content">Once again, I have some questions distinguishing some pieces of Japanese grammar that are all connected in my head, but in a sort of mushy way.  I'd like maybe a clearer distinction between<br /><br />わりに／くせに／ても(or でも) and のに<br /><br />To me these all have an implied meaning of &quot;contrary to A, B&quot; but that can't be right.  So what are the different meanings between these?<br /><br />Thanks in advance.</div>

			

		</div>

		
			<dl class="postprofile" id="profile164186">
			<dt>
				<a href="http://thejapanesepage.com/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=94193&amp;sid=afdf1483b436d49534d9f60bd1de6d37">DarumaBlue</a>
